title: SFH leads seven-day visit to three European countries
content_text:
p>
The Secretary for Food and Health, Dr York Chow, will lead a delegation to visit 
the United Kingdom and Germany to study the latest developments in children's 
hospitals and neuroscience institutes before attending the 61st World Health 
Assembly in Geneva, Switzerland. On the first stop of his visit to London on May 14, Dr Chow will visit the Great 
Ormond Street Hospital for Children which is a leading centre of excellence for 
special paediatric services and for research, evaluation and education in child

special paediatric services and for research, evaluation and education in child 
health. He will then tour the National Hospital for Neurology and Neurosurgery 
and hold discussions with senior management of the hospitals to learn more from 
their experience. Dr Chow will be in Germany on the next day (May 15) for a visit to the 
International Neuroscience Institute and Hanover Children's Hospital in Hanover, 
to be followed by a visit to the Centre of Clinical Neuroscience Institute in

to be followed by a visit to the Centre of Clinical Neuroscience Institute in 
Frankfurt on May 16. The fact-finding trip to the UK and Germany will give the delegation a better 
understanding of overseas experience in running children's hospitals and 
neuroscience institutes. The experience drawn may help in the establishment of 
medical centres of excellence in paediatrics and neuroscience in Hong Kong, with 
a view to raising professional standards and enhancing patient care through

a view to raising professional standards and enhancing patient care through 
cross-fertilisation of expertise, enhanced research and training. Accompanying Dr Chow on the visit to the UK and Germany are the Permanent 
Secretary for Food and Health, Ms Sandra Lee, and the Director (Strategy and 
Planning) of the Hospital Authority, Dr Lo Su-vui. After his visit to Western Europe, Dr Chow will depart for Geneva to attend the 
World Health Organisation's 61st World Health Assembly on May 19. He will return to Hong Kong on May 20.
